{"title": "EU executive chief concerned Hungary emergency measures go too far", "link": "https://news.yahoo.com/eu-executive-chief-concerned-hungary-105710229.html", "description": "<p><a href=\"https://news.yahoo.com/eu-executive-chief-concerned-hungary-105710229.html\"><img src=\"http://l2.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/Y5jnzkJKNe3bqHM_Lge38A--/YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b247aD04Njt3PTEzMDs-/https://media.zenfs.com/en-US/reuters.com/898ce7a93229fafac45fc4724b699f96\" width=\"130\" height=\"86\" alt=\"EU executive chief concerned Hungary emergency measures go too far\" align=\"left\" title=\"EU executive chief concerned Hungary emergency measures go too far\" border=\"0\" ></a>European Commission President Ursula von der Leyen expressed concern on Thursday that coronavirus restriction measures taken by Hungary went too far and insisted they should be limited in time and subject to scrutiny.  Hungary's parliament on Monday granted Prime Minister Viktor Orban an open-ended right to rule by decree and introduced jail sentences for anyone hindering measures to curb the spread of the virus or spreading false information about the pandemic.  \"I am concerned that certain measures go too far and I am particularly concerned about the situation in Hungary,\" von der Leyen told a news conference on Thursday.<p><br clear=\"all\">", "date": "Thu, 02 Apr 2020 06:57:10 -0400", "categories": ["Yahoo News - Latest News & Headlines"], "source": ["Yahoo News - Latest News & Headlines"]}
